        {
            "name": "Alice Montefiore Lucas",
            "bio": "Alice Julia Lucas (née Montefiore) (2 August 1851 – 25 March 1935) was a British Jewish poet, translator, and communal worker. Alice Julia Montefiore was born in 1851, the elder daughter of Nathaniel M. Montefiore and Emma Goldsmid. Alongside her brother Claude Montefiore, she studied Judaism under Solomon Schechter at the Hochschule in Berlin. On 24 April 1873 she married barrister Henry Lucas, who later served as treasurer and vice-president of the United Synagogue. In 1900 she helped establish the Jewish Study Society, modelled after the Council of Jewish Women, of which she served as the first president. Lucas also sat on the women's committee of the Westminster Jews' Free School and its preparatory nursery, the Jews' Infant School.",
            "website": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_Lucas_(poet)",
            "avatar": "https://opensiddur.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/alice-lucas-96x96.jpg",
            "profile_link": "https://opensiddur.org/profile/alice-lucas"
        }
    ],
